  "chunk_index": 36,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot meets with a prosecutor, Inspector Ruggles, and other officials to discuss a disappearance. Poirot asserts that the motive is simple and claims he possesses irrefutable evidence, including a real estate transaction document involving wealthy clients in the West Indies and the Mediterranean. He further claims that within 24 hours, he will provide a witness who saw a murder. Poirot expresses fear for this witness's safety, describing the antagonist as a ruthless and potentially insane individual. While the prosecutor remains skeptical of Poirot, calling him a charlatan, the police commissioner and Inspector Lugg express confidence in his abilities.\n\nMeanwhile, Mrs. Oliver and Judith Butler are having lunch at the Black Child restaurant with Miranda. When Miranda fails to return from the restroom, Judith searches the premises and the garden but cannot find her. Elsewhere, Inspector Goodwin informs Eustacia Mackay that a body has been found in a well; he confirms the victim was stabbed to death, indicating murder rather than suicide.\n\nIn reality, Miranda has not been murdered. She slipped out of the restaurant through a garden door and entered a car driven by a man with gray hair and a beard. The man drives her toward the Canterbury Hills to view the Double Axes and the Canterbury Stone Circle. Later, Mrs. Oliver calls Poirot in London to report that Miranda is missing and mentions a sighting of her entering a car with an old man. Poirot informs her that a body has been found in a well, though Mrs. Oliver is unaware of this discovery.",
